## Objective

The purpose of this lab was to study and implement two widely used balanced tree data structures: the **Red-Black Tree** and the **B-Tree**. These structures are designed to maintain balanced heights, enabling efficient insertion, deletion, and search operations even as the amount of stored data increases.

---

# Red-Black Tree

A Red-Black Tree is a self-balancing Binary Search Tree (BST) that uses node coloring and rotations to maintain balance after updates.

## Characteristics

The tree follows a set of rules that ensure logarithmic height:

* Every node is assigned either a Red or Black color.
* The root node must always be Black.
* A Red node cannot have a Red child.
* Every path from a node to a NULL leaf contains the same number of Black nodes.
* Newly inserted nodes are initially colored Red.

These constraints prevent the tree from becoming heavily skewed.

## Implemented Features

The Red-Black Tree implementation includes:

* Node insertion
* Left rotation
* Right rotation
* Color adjustment (recoloring)
* Inorder traversal

## Complexity Analysis

| Operation | Time Complexity |
| --------- | --------------- |
| Search    | O(log n)        |
| Insert    | O(log n)        |
| Traversal | O(n)            |

