# Conclusion

This experiment explored the implementation of two important balanced tree structures in C++. Both data structures ensure efficient searching and updating by preventing excessive tree growth.

The Red-Black Tree maintains balance through rotations and color adjustments, while the B-Tree relies on splitting, borrowing, and merging operations. Because of their efficiency and scalability, these structures are fundamental components of modern database management systems and indexing mechanisms.
